<sections><clause id="_the_relation_between_the_numbers_iim_r_and_iib_j" obligation="normative" displayorder="1">
<title depth="1">1.<tab/>The relation between the numbers <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub></math><!-- (M)_((r)) --></stem> and <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></math><!-- (B)_((j)) --></stem></title>
<p id="_b3c3ae70-4905-e4bd-f3e2-0d2f6336217d">In our recent study <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]">[1]</eref> on alternate sums of powers of integers, i.e. of sums of the type</p>

<formula id="eq1"><name>1</name><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mo>ℤ</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><mo>,</mo><mtext> with </mtext><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo></math><!-- ()_((r)) (ZZ)_((n)) = (sum)_((j = 1))^((n)) (- 1)^j j^r , \ with\ r = 1 , 2 , ... , --></stem></formula>

<p id="_d0c26d69-63a5-fda2-a991-905ddcf3ab3e">it was shown that they can be expressed in the form</p>

<formula id="eq2"><name>2</name><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mo>ℤ</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></munderover><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>μ</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><msup><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><mo>,</mo></math><!-- ()_((r)) (ZZ)_((n)) = (sum)_((j = 1))^((r - 1)) ()_((r)) (mu)_((j)) t^j + ((1))/((2)) (- 1)^n (2 t)^r , --></stem></formula>

<p id="_b1588164-4122-9fec-f3a2-69cee2de534a">where <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mfenced open="[" close="]"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math><!-- t = [((n + 1))/((2))] --></stem> is given by the number of terms in <xref target="eq1">Equation (1)</xref>, while <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>μ</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></math><!-- ()_((r)) (mu)_((j)) --></stem> are coefficients that have been tabulated.</p>

<p id="_8aa8abc5-3cf7-59f9-fdbb-0060b4581b0c">We found that these coefficients can be expressed by the “basic” integers <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><mo>≡</mo><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>μ</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></math><!-- (M)_((r)) -= ()_((r)) (mu)_((1)) --></stem>, since</p>

<formula id="eq3"><name>3</name><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>μ</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></msup><mi>r</mi><mo>!</mo></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>!</mo><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>−</mo><mi>j</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>!</mo></mrow></mrow></mfrac><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>−</mo><mi>j</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></msub><mo>,</mo><mtext> for </mtext><mi>r</mi><mo>&#x3e;</mo><mi>j</mi></math><!-- ()_((r)) (mu)_((j)) = ((2^(j - 1) r !))/((j ! (r - j + 1) !)) (M)_((r - j + 1)) , \ for\ r > j --></stem></formula>

<p id="_a556e4d7-cf2a-bbf4-e6cc-cd7b624c6d47">The alternate sum <xref target="eq1">Equation (1)</xref>, written in powers of <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>t</mi></math><!-- t --></stem>, thus begins for <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>r</mi></math><!-- r --></stem> even with</p>

<formula id="eq4"><name>4</name><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mo>ℤ</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>μ</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msup><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo></math><!-- ()_((r)) (ZZ)_((n)) = (M)_((r)) t + ()_((r)) (mu)_((2)) t^2 + ... , --></stem></formula>

<p id="_bc4b10b7-8130-1a1b-3776-a7ad9e940890">whereas for <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>r</mi></math><!-- r --></stem> odd there is no term proportional to <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>t</mi></math><!-- t --></stem>.</p>

<p id="_9b353682-7b07-d5d0-a88a-f464b48dff7e">It appears that the numbers <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub></math><!-- (M)_((r)) --></stem> play a role similar to that of the well-known Bernoulli numbers <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></math><!-- (B)_((j)) --></stem> which occur in the study of the sums</p>

<formula id="eq5"><name>5</name><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>≡</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><mo>.</mo></math><!-- ()_((r)) (S)_((n)) -= (sum)_((j = 1))^((n)) j^r . --></stem></formula>

<p id="_7c7f55be-5a30-a345-a6a9-ba12d41215dc">Some similarities between the numbers <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></math><!-- (B)_((j)) --></stem> and <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub></math><!-- (M)_((r)) --></stem> have already been noted in <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]">[1]</eref>, but it has not been possible to establish a clear link between the two series. It is the purpose of the present Note to make up for this deficiency. Some familiarity with <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]">[1]</eref> will make the reading easier.</p>

<p id="_62e1cdb8-3dfd-c7f2-d321-ddd2d56caa8f">The idea is to use the fact that the numbers <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub></math><!-- (M)_((r)) --></stem> are the coefficients of <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>t</mi></math><!-- t --></stem>, as shown in <xref target="eq4">Equation (4)</xref>. If we can subdivide <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mo>ℤ</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub></math><!-- ()_((r)) (ZZ)_((n)) --></stem> into a sum of contributions of type <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub></math><!-- ()_((r)) (S)_((n)) --></stem> and determine the coefficients of the linear terms <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>t</mi></math><!-- t --></stem> (in which the Bernoulli numbers occur), it must be possible to obtain the required relation by comparison of the respective coefficients.</p>

<p id="_6a18ad0a-dbda-8276-aa1e-8634e5380f22">Let us begin by decomposing the alternate sum <xref target="eq1">Equation (1)</xref> in a suitable way — the very  rearrangement we tried to avoid in <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]">[1]</eref>. Since <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>n</mi></math><!-- n --></stem> is even, we can put <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>n</mi><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><mi>t</mi></math><!-- n // 2 = t --></stem>. Then</p>

<formula id="eq6"><name>6</name><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mo>ℤ</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>j</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><mo>−</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>j</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup></math><!-- ()_((r)) (ZZ)_((n)) = (sum)_((j = 1))^((t)) (2 j)^r - (sum)_((j = 1))^((t)) (2 j - 1)^r --></stem></formula>

<formula id="_24dff6cb-c193-59de-9a0c-fcc4e6e685b3" unnumbered="true"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><mo>−</mo><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow></munderover><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></munderover><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>r</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>k</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msup></math><!-- = 2^r (sum)_((j = 1))^((t)) j^r - 2^r (((1))/((2)))^r (sum)_((j = 1))^((t)) (sum)_((k = 0))^((r)) ([[r],[k]]) (- 2)^k j^k --></stem></formula>

<formula id="_ee1dde97-68f9-0285-8d75-148e7634de10" unnumbered="true"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></munderover><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>r</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>k</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msup><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub></math><!-- = 2^r ()_((r)) (S)_((n)) - (sum)_((k = 0))^((r)) ([[r],[k]]) (- 2)^k ()_((k)) (S)_((n)) --></stem></formula>

<formula id="_1464ef96-7651-4248-63a1-12e9249dcd2d" unnumbered="true"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo>=</mo><mo>−</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></munderover><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>r</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>k</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msup><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>.</mo></math><!-- = - (sum)_((k = 0))^((r - 1)) ([[r],[k]]) (- 2)^k ()_((k)) (S)_((n)) . --></stem></formula>

<p id="_18640f1c-49b6-7a05-bf51-b9995c41f003">Let us now look at the development of a Bernoullian sum <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub></math><!-- ()_((r)) (S)_((n)) --></stem>. From relation (23) given in <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]">[1]</eref> we conclude that, for <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>r</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>2</mn></math><!-- r >= 2 --></stem> and even,</p>

<formula id="eq7"><name>7</name><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></mfrac><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>r</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msup><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>−</mo><mi>r</mi></mrow></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>+</mo><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><mi>t</mi><mo>.</mo></math><!-- ()_((r)) (S)_((n)) = ... + ((1))/((r)) ([[r],[r - 1]]) (B)_((r)) t^(r + 1 - r) = ... + (B)_((r)) t . --></stem></formula>

<p id="_649fde06-a2f1-a662-7036-cfa570b4baba">We note in passing that <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub></math><!-- ()_((r)) (S)_((n)) --></stem> with <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>r</mi></math><!-- r --></stem> odd has no terms proportional to <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>t</mi></math><!-- t --></stem> as the development stops at <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msup><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math><!-- t^2 --></stem>, exactly as for <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mo>ℤ</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub></math><!-- ()_((r)) (ZZ)_((n)) --></stem>.</p>

<p id="_53a9a873-9e61-226b-c713-db8f1acd697a">The two cases with <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math><!-- r = 0 --></stem> and <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math><!-- r = 1 --></stem> appearing in <xref target="eq6">Equation (6)</xref> have to be treated separately. One finds</p>

<formula id="eq8"><name>8</name><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>t</mi></math><!-- ()_((0)) (S)_((n)) = t --></stem></formula>

<p id="_ddb95597-c09a-e5cf-9138-c2b11309256d">and</p>

<formula id="_cc948f5c-e639-b15b-61fd-957283e43c6b" unnumbered="true"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><msup><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>.</mo></math><!-- ()_((1)) (S)_((n)) = ((1))/((2)) t + ((1))/((2)) t^2 . --></stem></formula>

<p id="_d88ac9e2-1cae-757e-8212-af0be9a51f6c">A look at <xref target="eq4">Equation (4)</xref> shows that the value of <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub></math><!-- (M)_((r)) --></stem> can be obtained from <xref target="eq6">Equation (6)</xref> by assembling the coefficients of <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>t</mi></math><!-- t --></stem> appearing in <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub></math><!-- ()_((k)) (S)_((n)) --></stem>. Writing <xref target="eq6">Equation (6)</xref> as</p>

<formula id="eq9"><name>9</name><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mo>ℤ</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>−</mo><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></munderover><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>r</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>k</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msup><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>,</mo></math><!-- ()_((r)) (ZZ)_((n)) = - ()_((0)) (S)_((n)) + 2 (r)_((1)) (S)_((n)) - (sum)_((k = 2))^((r - 1)) ([[r],[k]]) (- 2)^k ()_((k)) (S)_((n)) , --></stem></formula>

<p id="_ce0c15bb-ca23-dbd5-1029-9c6ba837d654">we find, with <xref target="eq7">Equation (7)</xref> and <xref target="eq8">Equation (8)</xref>,</p>

<formula id="eq10"><name>10</name><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>r</mi><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>−</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></munderover><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>r</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>j</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msup><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></math><!-- (M)_((r)) = - 1 + 2 r ((1))/((2)) - (sum)_((j = 2))^((r - 1)) ([[r],[j]]) (- 2)^j (B)_((j)) --></stem></formula>

<formula id="_c95b14f6-8aa6-28b6-3c21-198d91cb334b" unnumbered="true"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo>=</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>−</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mtext>, (even)</mtext></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>r</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>j</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>,</mo></math><!-- = r - 1 - (sum)_((j = 2 , (even)))^((r - 2)) 2^j ([[r],[j]]) (B)_((j)) , --></stem></formula>

<p id="_31ffb0c0-a450-9507-cd4e-9c4ac9e99b61">This is the relation looked for. It shows that the two series of numbers <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub></math><!-- (M)_((r)) --></stem> and <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></math><!-- (B)_((j)) --></stem> are indeed closely linked, and relation <xref target="eq10">Equation (10)</xref> is even somewhat reminiscent of the recurrence formula (18) found previously in <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]">[1]</eref>. It may be worthwhile noting that the sum in <xref target="eq10">Equation (10)</xref> yields an even integer.</p>

<p id="_3d8bab65-0f28-3ca9-6ddd-7ad1475ba6b2">Let us check (10) with three practical applications.</p>

<ul id="_6db2c6ea-dec1-bbad-5138-292773365c8e"><li><p id="_100c8c78-5303-4785-83a7-f6163d3b2123">For = 8:</p>
<formula id="_26a04941-7df7-89da-3f7a-2a76e2722f3b" unnumbered="true"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>8</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>−</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>8</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>j</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></math><!-- (M)_((8)) = 8 - 1 - (sum)_((j = 2))^((6)) 2^j ([[8],[j]]) (B)_((j)) --></stem></formula>

