<p id="_cbef5634-add7-a036-1b11-ce078d15352d">All these results agree with the numerical values given in <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]">[1]</eref>.</p>

<p id="_258d50bc-4ff5-bca9-2d01-73337c8ce6cd">Obviously, the existence of the new relation <xref target="eq10">Equation (10)</xref> does not me an that the numbers <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub></math><!-- (M)_((r)) --></stem> become superfluous; their practical usefulness is obvious in <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]">[1]</eref>. In any case, <xref target="eq10">Equation (10)</xref> is a very useful tool for their numerical evaluation, since it is a simple relation making use only of the Bernoulli numbers, which are readily available in tabular form, for example up to <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>60</mn></mrow></msub></math><!-- (B)_((60)) --></stem> in <eref type="inline" bibitemid="abramowitz" citeas="[2]">[2]</eref>.</p>
